</p>
<p>bastards (criminals) if they threaten you or the community. You must not worry about the 
regulations,&#8221; said Deputy Safety and Security Minister Susan Shabangu. &#8220;I want no warning shots, 
you have one shot and it must be a kill shot... I want to assure the police station commissioners and 
policemen and women from these areas that they have permission to kill these criminals.&#8221;) See also 
Al-Jazeera English, &#8220;Outrage at shoot-to-kill call&#8221; (11 April 2008). 
</p>
<p> 158 David Smith, &#8220;South Africa considers shoot-to-kill policy ahead of world cup&#8221; Guardian (16 
September 2009) (&#8220;Cele [the police commissioner] has called for a change in legislation that would 
allow police to open fire on suspects without having to worry about &#8220;what happens after that&#8221;.&#8221; The 
Police Minister was quoted as stating, &#8220;We are tired of waving nice documents like the constitution 
and the human rights charter in criminals&#8217; faces &#8230; We are going to meet these thugs head on, and if it 
means we kill when we shoot, then so be it.&#8221;).  
</p>
<p> 159 Bronwen Manby, &#8220;The South African Independent Complaints Directorate&#8221;, in Andrew J Goldsmith 
